<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
Time Off: Diversions and Excursions Jan 15-28</HL>
<DD> 01/15/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
      ART
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.: "The Age of Sultan Suleyman the Magnificent" -- More than 200 colorful, bejeweled objects of the Ottoman Empire under Suleyman (1520-66), a devoted patron of the arts. 
Included are illustrated manuscripts, drawings, paintings, textiles and ceramics. 
Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW. Jan. 25-May 17. 

   Cleveland Museum of Art: "Impressionist and Post-Impressionist Masterpieces: The Courtauld Collection" -- 48 paintings from one of the world's greatest collections of avant-garde works in France between 1870 and 1910. 
Cezanne, Gauguin, Monet, Manet, Renoir and Seurat are among those represented. 11150 East Boulevard. 
Through March 8. 
The show then travels to The Metropolitan Museum of Art, Manhattan (Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street), April 4-June 21; Kimbell Art Museum, Fort Worth, Texas (3333 Camp Bowie Boulevard), July 11-Sept. 27; the Art Institute of Chicago (Michigan Avenue and Adams), Oct. 17, 1987-Jan. 3, 1988; and the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art (4525 Oak St.), Kansas City, Mo., Jan. 30-April 3, 1988. 

   Los Angeles County Museum of Art: "Renaissance Master Bronzes From the Kunsthistorisches Museum, Vienna" -- 75 Italian and northern European bronzes that were collected by members of the royal houses of Austria and the Holy Roman Empire over a 400-year period. 
Subjects range from the madonna to satyrs and animals. 5905 Wilshire Boulevard. 
Through March 1. 

   DANCE
   Armitage Ballet: The provocative Karole Armitage, whose choreography has been called everything from classical to punk, brings her new company to Manhattan's Joyce Theater for a week of performances. 
Guests Stephanie Saland and Robert La Fosse from the New York City Ballet join the troupe in the world premiere of "Les Stances a Sophie"; the company also performs "Like a Rolling Stone," which is set to Bob Dylan music from "Highway '61 Revisited." 175 Eighth Ave. (at 19th St.). 
Jan. 20-25. (212) 242-0800. 

   Annabelle Gamson/Dance Solos, a company of five modern dancers, presents a program of classics by German Mary Wigman and American Eleanor King; and the world premiere of Ms. Gamson's "Tanzlieder" ("Dance Songs"), set to music by Brahms. 
St. Mark's Church, 10th Street and 2nd Avenue. 
Jan. 22-25. (212) 924-0070. 

   FESTIVAL
   Eleventh Annual Handel Festival, Washington, opens with tenor James McCracken singing the title role of Handel's "Joshua," a little-known 1747 oratorio in three acts. 
The cast also includes Lorna Haywood of the Royal Opera, Covent Garden, and the English National Opera; and Met basso Jan Opalach. 
Kennedy Center Concert Hall, 2700 F St. NW. Jan. 18. (202) 857-0900. 

   MUSIC
   Houston Grand Opera presents George Gershwin's "Porgy and Bess," a tale of the tenement life of South Carolina's Catfish Row. 
Bass-baritones Donnie Ray Albert and Mic Bell alternate as Porgy; Sopranos Carmen Balthrop and Henrietta Davis as Bess. 
John DeMain conducts. 
Jones Hall for the Performing Arts, 615 Louisiana St. Jan. 16, 17, 18, 20, 21, 23, 24 and 25. (713) 227-ARTS. 

   Lyric Opera of Chicago: Bulgarian diva Ghena Dimitrova sings of suicide as "La Gioconda." 
Her fellow gondoliers include Giuliano Ciannella and Alexandrina Milcheva, with Bruno Bartoletti conducting. 20 North Wacker Drive. 
Jan. 17, 20, 23, 26, 29 and 31. (312) 332-2244. 

   Washington Opera: Patricia Schumann gets a crown, but also Nero in "The Coronation of Poppea" by Claudio Monteverdi. 
Terrace Theater, Kennedy Center, 2600 F St. NW. Jan. 19, 21, 23, 25, 27 and 31; Feb. 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 14. (202) 857-0900. 

   THEATER
   Winterfest 7: Yale Repertory Theatre's seventh annual presentation of plays-in-progress (The cast and crew focus on the process of developing a script instead of creating a finished product). 
Offerings include Ivan Menchell's "The Cemetery Club" and Wakako Yamauchi's "The Memento" at the Repertory Theatre, Chapel and York Streets; Wendy MacLeod's "Apocalyptic Butterflies" and David Epstein's "Exact Change" at University Theatre, 222 York St. Through Feb. 7. (203) 432-1234. 

